{"word":"προσφωνέω","slug":"προσφωνέω","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>προσφωνέω</b></el> <el>(<a href='S:future tense'>fut.</a> <el>ήσω</el>) </el><p/><div class='li500'><b>I. </b><i>to call</i> or <i>speak to, address, accost</i>, <el>τινά</el> <b><a href='S:Homer'>Hom.</a></b>, <a href='S:et cetera'>etc.</a>; <a href='S:absolute, absolutely'>absol.</a>, <b><a href='S:Odyssey'>Od.</a></b>; <el>τοῖσιν προσεφώνεε</el> <i>addressed</i> [them] in these words, <b><a href='S:Odyssey'>Od.</a></b>; (but <a href='S:cum'>c.</a> <a href='S:dative'>dat.</a> <a href='S:person, personal'>pers.</a>, <b><a href='S:New Testament'>NTest.</a></b>):—<a href='S:cum'>c.</a> dupl. <a href='S:accusative'>acc.</a> <i>to address</i> words <i>to</i> a person, <b><a href='S:Iliad'>Il.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Euripides'>Eur.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>2. </b><i>to call by name</i>, <b><a href='S:Euripides'>Eur.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>II. </b><a href='S:cum'>c.</a> <a href='S:accusative'>acc.</a> rei, <i>to pronounce, utter</i>, <b><a href='S:Sophocles'>Soph.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}